\begin_layout Section
Tracking Methods 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Numerous algorithms can be used for localization in a wireless mesh network.
 All algorithms can be categorized into three general methods of localization.
 These are proximity method, scene analysis method and triangulation method
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Proximity method uses sensor or nodes that would be able to identify a target
 near its vicinity or area 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1"

\end_inset

.
 Sensors would look for signals sent by a target using transceivers or RFID
 tags.
 Usually a lot of nodes are positioned in different sections to cover the
 area of localization.
 Proximity method is known for its robustness because of its ability handle
 some interference cause by the environment, and also because of its low
 cost setup.
 Despite of that, the method is only able to detect the vicinity of a target
 and not the exact location itself thus decreasing its accuracy.
 It is also not easy to arrange, since sensors should be positioned correctly
 or confusion regarding the location of a target can happen.
 It is usually used in small areas or indoor setups.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, scene analysis method studies the area of localization
 to gather the signal strength of the target from a fixed sensor node with
 a given location.
 The signal strength would be tabulated along with its corresponding position
 to a database 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "1"

\end_inset

.
 After the analysis and installation, localization would start and sensors
 would compare the acquired signal strength of the target to the ones stored
 inside the database.
 Even if there is a database, sensors would still need to estimate the location
 since not all signal strengths can be mapped to a particular position on
 the area.
 Scene analysis method usually provides an accurate position but at the
 expense of time of analysis.
 If there is a large area of localization, especially in an outdoor environment,
 it would definitely take time to gather the signal strength at multiple
 positions.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last method is triangulation, which needs at least three base stations
 with known coordinates.
 These base stations are essential in locating a target since the acquired
 signal strengths per base station would be used to calculate the distance
 between the station and the target.
 Using the stations as centers and the calculated distance to the target
 as radii for each circle, the three circles would intersect at a common
 point which would provide the location of the target.
 Sometimes the location is not accurate because of signal strength discrepancies
 so other methods were developed with triangulation as their basis.
 These are Coverage Area Based Algorithm and Ring Overlapping Localization
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "4794164"

\end_inset

.
 This method is ideal for outdoor localization since base stations are capable
 of a large coverage area but targets require a high amount of energy for
 transmitting data.
 The transceivers of the target would likely need an immediate access to
 charging in this method.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Distance Measurement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The three main types of distance measurement methods are the signal transmission
 time based, signal transmission route based and signal transmission power
 based or Receive Signal Strength Identifier (RSSI).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first method uses time of arrival (TOA) of a signal to determine the
 distance between two nodes.
 It starts out when a node (sender) sends a signal to another node (receiver).
 The receiver would then send back a reply signal.
 After the reply signal is received by the sender time is measured using
 a synchronize clock referred to by the nodes.
 It is very hard to synchronize multiple nodes particularly in WMN which
 would consist of large number of nodes.
 Another disadvantages is that the speed of a radio frequency, which is
 primally used in node, are difficult to measure.
 To solve this problem another time based method was developed using the
 time difference of arrival.
 This method uses two signals, particularly an RF signal and a supersonic
 signal.
 Supersonic was chosen since their speeds are easier to measure relative
 to the RF signal.
 The method starts when a sender send an RF signal to a receiver, then the
 sender would send another signal this time the supersonic signal.
 The receiver would measure the difference in time of arrival of the two
 signals and by using the calculated speed of the supersonic signal the
 distance can be obtained.
 Even though it solves the problem of speed measurement it would require
 each node to have a supersonic transmitter and receiver which increases
 the cost of a node.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Signal transmission route based algorithms use the hop count attribute.
 In this method some nodes know their own location since they are static.
 Using the hop count and the location of the static nodes the a target can
 locate itself and the target will forward its location to a server or sink.
 The method yields low accuracy since the hop count is sometimes not proportiona
l to the distance between nodes.
 Systems who usually use this are those with regularly distributed nodes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The last algorithm is based on the signal power or RSSI.
 Using a formula that convert the strength of a signal to distance, the
 distance between nodes can be easily computed.
 There is also no need of additional transmitters and receivers since the
 RF signals are can already be used in RSSI measurements.
 The only problem this method possesses is that interferences caused by
 other signals and obstruction will change the value of the RSSI which will
 lead to errors in localization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
WLAN Localization Methods
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Localization in WLAN can be differentiated into 4 kinds of algorithms.
 These are experimental algorithms, statistic algorithms, signal transmission
 based algorithms, and hybrid algorithms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Experimental algorithms consists of two stages an offline and an online
 stage.
 Offline stages of experimental algorithms main objective is to create a
 database of signal strength with its corresponding location.
 To do this a target is moved to different locations and the signal strengths
 obtained will be tabulated.
 When the network becomes online the target can easily be located using
 its signal strength because it can be directly mapped to a location using
 the database.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Statistics algorithms requires data that will be used as a training set
 for the network to learn using statistic models.
 Unlike the previous algorithm, it requires less work in terms of data gathering
 because the data set is only acquired in some sections of the region of
 surveillance.
 Its drawback is the amount of time needed in order to fully train the network,
 which is also considered as an offline work.
 After training, there might still be errors in localization brought by
 using training sets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Signal transmission based algorithms requires no offline work unlike the
 first two methods.
 It uses signal strengths of multiple nodes to perform trilateration in
 order to localize a target.
 It uses the distances converted from the signal strength and then used
 as values for the equations.
 GPS is one of the major users of this algorithm.
 Its disadvantage is that interferences will create discrepancies in the
 signal strength yielding to incorrect locations of a target.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Hybrid algorithms from the name itself is a hybrid between experimental
 and signal transmission based algorithms.
 It uses calculations to locate a target like signal transmission based
 algorithms.
 The data acquired by the from the offline phase is used to verify the signal
 strengths that will be used in the calculations.
 The measure signal strength is not always associated to the database, to
 improve the overall effectiveness of the metod.
\end_layout

