 Using a code whose function is to send a signal to a that will control
 a blinking LED of a Wizzimote using another Wizzimote.
 We would collect the necessary data, which are the RSSI of the Wizzimote
 and also the minimum and maximum ranges for an outdoor environment.
 After collecting the data we would be able to know if it is an optimal
 sensor node for a Target Tracking system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Trilateration Method Testing
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the Wizzimotes are optimal, we would test the accuracy of the Triangulation
 Method next.
 We will position the sensor nodes in the corners of a room, this nodes
 will become the anchors.
 We would label each anchor with x and y coordinates, which are dependent
 on the height and the width of the room.
 The target would be positioned in an unknown location to be tracked by
 the anchors.
 After calculations from the anchors, we would try to match the results
 obtained by the anchors to the actual measurement which would be manually
 measured.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
After the indoor testing, we would then test it on the outdoor environment,
 and this a larger region would be involved.
 Using the same steps used on the indoor testing, we would be able to test
 the accuracy of the method.
 Interferences may come in to play, since the anchors might be positioned
 with buildings or trees in between them.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For both indoor and outdoor testing we would repeat the steps multiple times
 to acquire relative data about the accuracy of the method.
 That data will be used to minimize the descrepancies of the calculated
 location of a target.
